You can generalize this method by associating a function with each element of the dictionary:

    def do_red():
        return &#39;red&#39;
    
    def do_blue():
        return &#39;blue&#39;
    
    def do_green():
        return &#39;green&#39;
    
    # map the inputs to the function blocks
    options = {1: do_red,
               2: do_blue,
               3: do_green}
    
    options[1]()
    
    # output: &#39;red&#39;

__NOTE__: If you want to have a default value when the key does not exist in the dictionary, you can access it this way:


    options.get(key, &#39;black&#39;) # or options.get(key, lambda: &#39;black&#39;)()


